S3.example:
$ aws s3api get-bucket-acl --bucket my-app-bucket
{
    "Owner": {
        "DisplayName": "prod-account",
        "ID": "a1b2c3...deadbeef"
    },
    "Grants": [
        {
            "Grantee": {"Type": "CanonicalUser", "ID": "a1b2c3...deadbeef"},
            "Permission": "FULL_CONTROL"
        },
        {
            "Grantee": {"Type": "Group", "URI": "http://acs.amazonaws.com/groups/global/AllUsers"},
            "Permission": "READ"
        }
    ]
}

What it means:
- A Grantee of type "Group" with the AllUsers URI and READ permission
  means the bucket (or specific object) is world-readable via ACL —
  this is the classic "public bucket" misconfiguration to grep for.
- Most modern buckets disable ACLs entirely (BucketOwnerEnforced) and
  rely solely on the bucket policy — check
  "aws s3api get-bucket-policy-status" if this call returns only the
  owner with no extra grants.

$ aws s3api get-bucket-location --bucket acme-backups-eu
{
    "LocationConstraint": "eu-west-2"
}

# us-east-1 returns null (quirk of the S3 API):
$ aws s3api get-bucket-location --bucket acme-us-bucket
{
    "LocationConstraint": null
}

# Useful for ensuring cross-region replication sources match:
#   aws s3api get-bucket-location --bucket <source-bucket>
# Verify from within an EC2 instance to detect cross-region access costs.

